The United States Open Tennis Championships is one of the four Grand Slam tennis tournaments held annually in late August through early September in New York City. Some key details:

- The tournament was first held in 1881 and has been played every year since. It moved to its current location at the USTA Billie Jean King National Tennis Center in 1978. 

- Notable achievements include John McEnroe winning his third consecutive men's singles title in 1980 and Serena Williams, nearly 32, winning the women's singles title in 2013, becoming the oldest champion in the Open Era.
